Palu and Donggala have been affected by tsunamis several times over a century, according to the Indonesian Agency for Disaster Reduction.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck western Donggala in 1996, killing nine people.
Indonesia is situated on the Pacific seismic circle and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Some of the main earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years are:
2004: A major earthquake, which occurred on 26 December on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, triggered a tsunami that spread over 14 countries, causing 226 000 casualties on the Indian Ocean coast, of which more than half were in Aceh.
2005: Several violent earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra in late March at the beginning of April.
