Info point on the red tide: Low concentration in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission indicates a general decrease in red tide concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties - which cause a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide covers about 209 km (130 miles) of coasts, from north of Pinellas to south of Lee County.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in the county of Pasco.
Moderate concentrations in or off the county of Pinellas were reported last week, low concentrations at high off the county of Hillsborough, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations at the bottom of Sarasota County or at large, medium concentrations in Charlotte County, and low concentrations in Lee County and off the latter, high concentrations at the bottom or wide in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
